# Skin

(A concept so fundamental, one wonders why it warrants such exhaustive explanation. But, since you insist.)

This article delves into the layer of [tissue](/Tissue_(biology)) that encases the bodies of [vertebrate](/Vertebrate) animals, a remarkably versatile and often overlooked organ. For a more focused discussion on the intricacies of this covering in *Homo sapiens*, one might consider perusing the article on [Human skin](/Human_skin). For those whose curiosity extends beyond this primary definition, a broader range of applications and meanings can be found at [Skin (disambiguation)](/Skin_(disambiguation)).

## Details
Identifiers [Latin](/Latin) cutis [MeSH](/Medical_Subject_Headings) D012867 [Anatomical terminology](/Anatomical_terminology)
&#91;edit on Wikidata]

Skin, in its most elementary description, is the usually soft, remarkably flexible outer [tissue](/Tissue_(biology)) that envelops the physical form of a [vertebrate](/Vertebrate). Its existence is predicated on three indispensable functions: the unwavering commitment to [protection](/Protection), the meticulous process of [regulation](/Regulation), and the often-underappreciated capacity for [sensation](/Sensation). One might almost consider it the body's primary negotiator with the chaos of the external world.

It's crucial to distinguish this [vertebrate](/Vertebrate) integument from other protective external structures, such as the rigid [arthropod exoskeleton](/Arthropod_exoskeleton). These alternative [animal coverings](/Cuticle) arise from entirely different [developmental origins](/Cellular_differentiation), possess distinct structural architectures, and are composed of markedly disparate [chemical compositions](/Chemical_composition). To conflate them would be a rather elementary error. The adjective "cutaneous," derived from the [Latin](/Latin) *cutis* meaning 'skin,' serves as a precise descriptor for anything pertaining to this organ – a term one might expect to encounter frequently in any serious discussion on the subject.

Within the class of [mammals](/Mammal), the skin transcends mere covering; it is an [organ](/Organ_(anatomy)) of the elaborate [integumentary system](/Integumentary_system). This system is meticulously constructed from multiple layers of [ectodermal](/Ectodermal) [tissue](/Tissue_(biology)), serving as a vigilant guard for the vulnerable underlying [muscles](/Muscle), the rigid framework of [bones](/Bone), the flexible connections of [ligaments](/Ligament), and the delicate [internal organs](/Internal_organs). However, the narrative of skin is not monolithic; forms of skin with fundamentally different characteristics are observed across [amphibians](/Amphibian), [reptiles](/Reptile), and [birds](/Bird), each exquisitely adapted to their specific environments and survival strategies. It is also worth noting that the skin, along with its associated cutaneous and subcutaneous tissues, plays profound, if often overlooked, roles in the formation, intricate structure, and precise function of various extraskeletal apparatuses. Consider, for instance, the formidable horns of bovids—such as domestic cattle—and rhinos, the annually shedding antlers of cervids, the distinctive ossicones of giraffids, the protective osteoderms of armadillos, and even the curious presence of the [os penis](/Os_penis) (baculum) or [os clitoris](/Os_clitoris) in certain mammalian species. These diverse structures all owe their existence and utility, in part, to the underlying dermal and subcutaneous layers.

A persistent myth suggests certain [mammals](/Mammal) are entirely hairless. This is, predictably, incorrect. All [mammals](/Mammal), without exception, possess at least some degree of hair on their skin. Even seemingly sleek [marine mammals](/Marine_mammal) such as the colossal [whales](/Whale), the intelligent [dolphins](/Dolphin), and the agile [porpoises](/Porpoise), which might appear entirely devoid of hair, retain vestigial follicles or scattered hairs, particularly during embryonic development or in specific regions of their bodies.

The skin's primary role as the interface with the external [environment](/Natural_environment) positions it as the body's undisputed first line of defense against a relentless barrage of external factors. For example, it plays a critical, often life-saving, role in shielding the [body](/Body_(biology)) from insidious [pathogens](/Pathogen) and, equally vital, preventing excessive and detrimental water loss. Beyond this crucial protective function, its repertoire extends to providing [thermal insulation](/Thermal_insulation), meticulously orchestrating [temperature regulation](/Thermoregulation), acting as a sophisticated organ of [sensation](/Sensation), and even participating in the vital biochemical process of [vitamin D](/Vitamin_D) synthesis, alongside its role in folate metabolism.

When skin suffers severe damage, the body's reparative mechanisms often lead to the formation of [scar tissue](/Scar). While functional, this tissue frequently presents with distinct characteristics, sometimes appearing discoloured or notably depigmented, a permanent, albeit often faded, record of past injury. The thickness of this remarkable organ is not uniform across an organism's body; it exhibits considerable variation depending on its anatomical location. In humans, for instance, the skin beneath the eyes and around the delicate eyelids represents the thinnest on the body, measuring a mere 0.5 mm in thickness. This area, unfortunately for those concerned with appearances, is often among the first to betray the passage of time, manifesting "crows feet" and other tell-tale [wrinkles](/Wrinkle). Conversely, the skin on the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet is the thickest, reaching a robust 4 mm, a testament to the constant friction and pressure these areas endure. Intriguingly, the efficiency and quality of [wound healing](/Wound_healing) in skin have been demonstrated to be significantly enhanced by the presence of [estrogen](/Estrogen).

[Fur](/Fur) is, quite simply, dense hair. Its primary biological purpose is to amplify the [thermal insulation](/Thermal_insulation) that the skin inherently provides, a critical adaptation for survival in diverse climates. However, fur can also serve as a prominent [secondary sexual characteristic](/Secondary_sex_characteristic), signaling fitness or reproductive status, or as an indispensable form of [camouflage](/Camouflage), allowing an animal to blend seamlessly into its surroundings and evade detection by predators or prey. In some animals, the skin develops into an exceptionally hard and thick integument, which, after specific processing, can be transformed into durable [leather](/Leather), a material prized for millennia.

[Reptiles](/Reptile) and the vast majority of [fish](/Fish) are endowed with hard, protective [scales](/Scale_(zoology)) covering their skin, offering a formidable defense against environmental hazards and predation. Similarly, [birds](/Bird) possess hard [feathers](/Feather), all of which are composed of tough [beta-keratins](/Beta-keratin), a structural protein distinct from the alpha-keratins found in mammalian hair and nails. In stark contrast, [amphibian](/Amphibian) skin is notably less robust as a barrier, particularly concerning the passage of chemicals. It is frequently subject to the relentless forces of [osmosis](/Osmosis) and [diffusion](/Diffusion). A rather vivid illustration of this permeability is the observation that a [frog](/Frog) immersed in an [anesthetic](/Anesthetic) solution will rapidly become sedated as the chemical readily diffuses through its porous skin. This inherent characteristic, however, is not a design flaw; [amphibian](/Amphibian) skin plays pivotal roles in their daily survival and their remarkable ability to exploit an astonishingly wide array of habitats and ecological niches.

On a rather recent note, biologists, on January 11, 2024, made headlines with the announcement of the discovery of the oldest known fossilized skin. This ancient integument, remarkably preserved for approximately 289 million years, is believed to have originated from an ancient [reptile](/Reptile), offering an unprecedented glimpse into the deep evolutionary history of this vital organ.

## Etymology

The linguistic journey of the word "skin" is, perhaps unsurprisingly, rooted in the practicalities of ancient life. Originally, the term referred exclusively to animal hide that had been dressed and tanned, intended for utilitarian purposes. For the covering of humans, the more archaic term "hide" was commonly employed. "Skin" itself is a direct borrowing from [Old Norse](/Old_Norse) *skinn*, which also denoted "animal hide, fur." Tracing its lineage further back, we arrive at the [Proto-Indo-European](/Proto-Indo-European) root *sek-*, meaning "to cut." This etymological origin likely serves as a stark, if somewhat brutal, reference to the ancient practice of cutting off animal hides to fashion garments or other essential items. A pragmatic, if not entirely poetic, origin for such a pervasive term.

## Structure in mammals

(For those who appreciate the finer points of biological architecture, here's how mammals manage to keep their insides, well, *inside*.)

### Details
Identifiers [MeSH](/Medical_Subject_Headings) D012867 [Anatomical terminology](/Anatomical_terminology)
&#91;edit on Wikidata]

Mammalian skin, a marvel of biological engineering, is fundamentally organized into two principal layers, each with distinct yet complementary roles in maintaining the organism's integrity:

*   The [epidermis](/Epidermis), the superficial stratum, which masterfully provides both waterproofing capabilities and serves as an impenetrable barrier against the insidious threat of infection. It's the outer wall, so to speak.
*   The [dermis](/Dermis), situated beneath the epidermis, acting as the robust foundation and the crucial anatomical host for the various specialized [appendages](/Appendages) of the skin, such as hair follicles and glands.

### Epidermis

(The first line of defense, often taken for granted until it's compromised.)

The [epidermis](/Epidermis) constitutes the outermost strata of the skin, a thin yet formidable protective barrier meticulously engineered over the body's surface. Its primary, non-negotiable responsibilities include the critical containment of bodily fluids, preventing undue water loss, and, equally vital, acting as an unyielding bulwark against the ingress of [pathogens](/Pathogen). Structurally, it is classified as a stratified squamous [epithelium](/Epithelium), a tissue type characterized by multiple layers of flattened cells. This complex architecture is primarily composed of continuously [proliferating](/Cell_division) basal [keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) and their subsequent [differentiated](/Cell_differentiation) suprabasal counterparts.

[Keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) are, in essence, the workhorses of the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)), comprising a staggering 95% of its cellular population. While they dominate, other specialized [cells](/Cell_(biology)) are also strategically dispersed throughout this layer, contributing to its multifaceted functions. These include [Merkel cells](/Merkel_cell), which play a role in touch sensation; [melanocytes](/Melanocyte), responsible for pigment production and UV protection; and [Langerhans cells](/Langerhans_cell), which are crucial components of the immune system.

For a more granular understanding, the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)) itself can be further meticulously subdivided into distinct strata, or layers, typically enumerated from the outermost surface inward:

*   The [Stratum corneum](/Stratum_corneum): The superficial, highly keratinized layer, composed of dead, flattened cells, serving as the ultimate protective shield.
*   The [Stratum lucidum](/Stratum_lucidum): A translucent layer, found exclusively in the thick skin of the [palms](/Hand) of the hands and the [soles](/Sole_(foot)) of the feet, offering additional resilience.
*   The [Stratum granulosum](/Stratum_granulosum): Characterized by granular cells that are undergoing keratinization, preparing for their journey to the surface.
*   The [Stratum spinosum](/Stratum_spinosum): The "spiny layer," where cells are interconnected by desmosomes, providing structural integrity.
*   The [Stratum basale](/Stratum_basale) (also known as the stratum germinativum): The deepest layer, where continuous [cell division](/Cell_division) (mitosis) occurs, generating new [keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) to replenish the layers above.

The [keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) originating in the [stratum basale](/Stratum_basale) embark on a remarkable journey of [proliferation](/Cell_division) through [mitosis](/Mitosis). Their daughter [cells](/Cell_(biology)) then commence an upward migration through the various strata. As they ascend, these [cells](/Cell_(biology)) undergo profound transformations in both shape and [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition), a process of multiple stages of [cell differentiation](/Cell_differentiation) that ultimately renders them anucleated—devoid of a nucleus—by the time they reach the surface. Throughout this intricate process, [keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) become exquisitely organized, forming robust [cellular junctions](/Cell_junction), specifically [desmosomes](/Desmosomes), which create strong attachments between adjacent cells. Concurrently, they secrete specialized [keratin](/Keratin) [proteins](/Proteins) and various [lipids](/Lipids) that coalesce to form an [extracellular matrix](/Extracellular_matrix), collectively contributing immensely to the mechanical [strength](/Strength_of_materials) and barrier function of the skin. Ultimately, the [keratinocytes](/Keratinocyte) of the outermost [stratum corneum](/Stratum_corneum) are continuously shed from the surface in a process known as [desquamation](/Desquamation), making way for new cells from below.

A critical anatomical detail: the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)) is entirely devoid of its own [blood vessels](/Blood_vessel). Consequently, the metabolically active [cells](/Cell_(biology)) residing in its deepest layers must rely on the passive process of [diffusion](/Diffusion) for their nourishment, receiving vital substances from the [blood](/Blood) [capillaries](/Capillaries) that extend into the uppermost reaches of the adjacent [dermis](/Dermis). It's a rather efficient, if somewhat indirect, supply chain.

### Basement membrane

(The unseen border control, regulating what gets through and what doesn't. Crucial, yet always in the background.)

Serving as the critical interface between the [epidermis](/Epidermis) and the underlying [dermis](/Dermis) is the [basement membrane](/Basement_membrane). This exceedingly thin, yet remarkably robust, sheet of [fibers](/Fibers) is not merely a passive separator; it is a collaborative creation, painstakingly assembled through the combined actions of both these vital [tissues](/Tissue_(biology)).

The [basement membrane](/Basement_membrane) performs a dual role of paramount importance. Firstly, it meticulously controls the traffic of both [cells](/Cell_(biology)) and [molecules](/Molecules) as they attempt to traverse the boundary between the [dermis](/Dermis) and [epidermis](/Epidermis). This selective permeability is essential for maintaining the distinct environments and functions of each layer. Secondly, and perhaps more subtly, it functions as a dynamic reservoir. By binding a diverse array of [cytokines](/Cytokine) and [growth factors](/Growth_factors), the [basement membrane](/Basement_membrane) enables their controlled and localized release during periods of [physiological](/Physiological) remodeling—such as normal tissue turnover—or in response to injury during crucial repair processes. It's a master of controlled deployment.

### Dermis

(The workhorse layer, providing the structure and housing all the interesting bits.)

Beneath the intricate [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)) lies the [dermis](/Dermis), a substantial layer of skin primarily composed of [connective tissue](/Connective_tissue). This layer serves as a crucial cushion, adeptly absorbing and dissipating the various [stresses](/Stress_(biology)) and strains to which the body is constantly subjected. More than just a shock absorber, the [dermis](/Dermis) is the primary determinant of the skin's remarkable tensile [strength](/Strength_of_materials) and inherent [elasticity](/Elasticity_(physics)). These vital mechanical properties are conferred by its complex [extracellular matrix](/Extracellular_matrix), a finely woven network comprising robust [collagen fibrils](/Collagen_fibrils), delicate [microfibrils](/Microfibrils), and resilient [elastic fibers](/Elastic_fibers), all meticulously embedded within a hydrated gel of [hyaluronan](/Hyaluronan) and various [proteoglycans](/Proteoglycan).

It's worth noting that skin [proteoglycans](/Proteoglycan) are not a homogenous group; they exhibit considerable diversity and are strategically localized to very specific areas. For example, [hyaluronan](/Hyaluronan), [versican](/Versican), and [decorin](/Decorin) are broadly distributed throughout the [extracellular matrix](/Extracellular_matrix) of both the [dermis](/Dermis) and [epidermis](/Epidermis), contributing to hydration and structural organization. In contrast, [biglycan](/Biglycan) and [perlecan](/Perlecan) are found exclusively within the [epidermis](/Epidermis), highlighting their specialized roles in that superficial layer.

The [dermis](/Dermis) is also a veritable hub of sensory perception, densely populated with numerous [mechanoreceptors](/Mechanoreceptor)—specialized [nerve endings](/Nerve_endings) that collectively bestow the sense of [touch](/Touch), pressure, vibration, and temperature. This sensory capability is further refined by the presence of [nociceptors](/Nociceptor), which detect painful stimuli, and [thermoreceptors](/Thermoreceptor), which register variations in heat and cold. Beyond sensation, the [dermis](/Dermis) is the anatomical home to a multitude of essential skin [appendages](/Appendages), including the [hair follicles](/Hair_follicle), the [sweat glands](/Sweat_gland) (both eccrine and apocrine), the [sebaceous glands](/Sebaceous_gland) that produce sebum, the delicate [apocrine glands](/Apocrine_glands), a network of [lymphatic vessels](/Lymphatic_vessel) crucial for immune function, and a rich supply of [blood vessels](/Blood_vessel). These [blood vessels](/Blood_vessel) within the [dermis](/Dermis) are not merely passive conduits; they are actively responsible for providing essential nourishment and efficient waste removal for both their own resident [cells](/Cell_(biology)) and, as previously mentioned, for the overlying, avascular [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)).

Furthermore, compelling evidence suggests that the [dermis](/Dermis) and its associated subcutaneous tissues harbor germinative cells. These specialized cells are believed to be intricately involved in the formation and development of a variety of extra-skeletal apparatuses in [mammals](/Mammal), such as the aforementioned horns and osteoderms, underscoring the dynamic developmental potential embedded within these layers.

The [dermis](/Dermis) is intimately and robustly connected to the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)) via the intervening [basement membrane](/Basement_membrane). Structurally, it is conventionally delineated into two distinct regions: a more superficial area, directly adjacent to the epidermis, known as the **papillary region**, and a deeper, considerably thicker expanse referred to as the **reticular region**.

#### Papillary region

The papillary region, named for its distinctive finger-like projections, or papillae, is composed of loose [areolar connective tissue](/Areolar_connective_tissue). These papillae extend upwards, interdigitating with the downward projections of the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)). This intricate, undulating interface effectively creates a "bumpy" surface that significantly strengthens the mechanical connection between the two primary layers of the skin, preventing shearing forces from separating them. It's a clever design for structural integrity.

#### Reticular region

Positioned deep to the papillary region, the reticular region is typically far more substantial in thickness. It is architecturally defined by its composition of dense irregular [connective tissue](/Connective_tissue), and its name aptly reflects the dense, interwoven concentration of [collagenous](/Collagen), [elastic](/Elastic_fibers), and [reticular](/Reticular_fiber) fibers that form an intricate meshwork throughout its expanse. These robust [protein](/Protein) fibers are precisely what impart the [dermis](/Dermis) with its remarkable properties of tensile [strength](/Strength_of_materials), considerable [extensibility](/Extensibility) (the ability to stretch), and resilient [elasticity](/Elasticity_(physics)) (the capacity to recoil).

Within the expansive reticular region, one also finds the embedded [roots of the hair](/Roots_of_the_hair), the secretory [sweat glands](/Sweat_gland), the oil-producing [sebaceous glands](/Sebaceous_gland), various specialized [receptors](/Cutaneous_receptor) for sensory input, the foundational structures for [nails](/Nail_(anatomy)), and an extensive network of vital [blood vessels](/Blood_vessel). It's a veritable subterranean city of essential components.

### Subcutaneous tissue

(Not *technically* skin, but don't tell it that. It's too busy doing all the grunt work.)

The [subcutaneous tissue](/Subcutaneous_tissue), often referred to as the hypodermis, is, strictly speaking, not considered an integral part of the skin itself. Instead, it lies immediately beneath the [dermis](/Dermis), serving as the crucial anchoring layer that binds the skin securely to the underlying [bone](/Bone) and [muscle](/Muscle). Beyond its foundational role, it acts as a vital conduit, supplying the skin with its essential [blood vessels](/Blood_vessel) and intricate network of [nerves](/Nerve).

This layer is primarily composed of loose [connective tissue](/Connective_tissue) and resilient [elastin](/Elastin). The predominant [cell](/Cell_(biology)) types encountered here include [fibroblasts](/Fibroblast), which produce connective tissue components; [macrophages](/Macrophage), essential immune cells; and, most notably, [adipocytes](/Adipocyte), the specialized cells that store [fat](/Fat). Indeed, the [subcutaneous tissue](/Subcutaneous_tissue) can account for up to 50% of the body's total [body fat](/Body_fat). This adipose tissue serves multiple critical functions, primarily acting as a protective padding against physical impact and providing essential [thermal insulation](/Thermal_insulation) to regulate body temperature.

It’s worth acknowledging the ubiquitous presence of [microorganisms](/Microorganisms), such as [Staphylococcus epidermidis](/Staphylococcus_epidermidis), which naturally colonize the skin surface, forming a complex and dynamic ecosystem known as the [skin flora](/Skin_flora). The density of this microbial community varies significantly depending on the specific region of the skin. Even after rigorous disinfection, the skin surface is rapidly recolonized by [bacteria](/Bacteria) residing in deeper, protected niches, such as the [hair follicle](/Hair_follicle), and from adjacent mucosal surfaces like the [gastrointestinal tract](/Gastrointestinal_tract) and [urogenital](/Urogenital) openings. They're persistent, if nothing else.

